div.span: Example: two different customers in the same data center with two distinct 4096 VLAN ranges. They can only talk via L3 between each other, may have different subnets on their VLANs and their hosts are never in the same same boadcast domain (L2).

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: Each rackd is located either on a separate host in a rack or on one of the Top of the Rack switches. In this synthetic example MAAS is under control of a data center provider, not customers.

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: Naturally, two customers will have two distinct fabrics even though it is a single MAAS region installation. However, in a more general case, fabric-1 and fabric-2 can both be subdivided into multiple fabrics.

div.div: This diagram also includes spaces which are logical groupings of VLANs with subnets that are able to "communicate with each other". "communicate" is a bit of a vague description. In practice it means that there are layer 3 devices that are able to forward packets from each VLAN to all other VLANs (an L3 switch or a router), moreover, these L3 devices may or may not be directly connected to those VLANs. Hosts may either use that L3 device as a default gateway or have static routes, however, that next hop L3 device must be able to send L3 packets to the right destination as there is no other way to go from one L2 (broadcast domain) to the other.

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: Notice that fabrics and physical VLAN placement become irrelevant here - the fact that we use VLAN 10 on different fabrics does not concern us. Subnets are different in every VLAN. Some could be the same but this is a very complex network scenario which includes overlapping subnets and careful static route management and policy-based routing.

div.style: text-align: left

div.div: Routes are summarized via green lines, however, each layer 3 device must have a next hop to the final subnet - this is not just about end devices.
